Jason, you are right no-oping is the right way to go here. We are getting into this situation, due to single GII processing thread updating index for batch of entries. And processing the entry that is removed. Since we don't store any removed-entries (TOMBSTONEs) in index, we could just return if oldKeyValue returns null.
 // We know the old key so let's just remove mapping from the old key
      if (oldKeyValue != null) {
          if (oldKeyValue.get() == null) {
            return;
          }
        indexStore.removeMapping(oldKeyValue.get().getOldKey(), entry);
      }

We should add few DUnit test, reproducing the issue.

@pivotal-jbarrett The name `geode-log4j` is meant to describe this as the `log4j-core` implementation of Geode Logging as opposed to the yet-to-be-created `geode-logback` which would be the logback implementation of Geode Logging. The idea is that if you want to use `log4j-core` with Geode then drop this jar in your classpath. The pom dependency says `implementation` instead of `api` only because these classes don't provide user APIs that return `log4j-core` classes. These classes simply install an SPI provider that enables Geode log-level, log-file, etc to interact with `log4j-core`. Without these provider classes, the logging properties and logging GFSH commands do nothing.

This module will export `org.apache.geode.logging.log4j`. `geode-core` will export `org.apache.geode.logging` and `org.apache.geode.logging.spi`. (I have a few changes I still need to make).

I can move the Alerting classes from `alerting` packages into `logging` packages. I was originally intending to keep them separate even though both are implemented with `log4j-core` -- and could thus be implemented in `geode-logback` with `logback` instead.
